<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.51/1490.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Dominican Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 14.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dominican Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-01">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 1, 1915</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have the honor to send you
                            herewith a copy of the Gaceta Official No. 2569, of January 2, 1915,
                            which contains the decree<note n="6" xml:id="d285fn6">Not
                                printed.</note> dated December 26, 1914, by which President Jiménes
                            forbade the use of the stamps and stamped paper that formed part of the
                            internal revenue of the Dominican Republic.</p>
                        <p>I respectfully call your attention to the fact that that first step
                            toward the rehabilitation of the internal revenues is taken in
                            accordance with the State Department’s suggestions in the memorandum of
                            January 8 [9], 1915, and the telegram sent to Mr. Sullivan on the 12th
                            of the same month.</p>
                        <p>I renew [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Enrique Jiménez</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>